title: Cardiganshire
sources: [{"reference": "SP 12/39","date": "2 Jan 1566","folio": "1-4","notes": "The castles of Cardigan and Aberystwith 'beinge great annctient Casels in Great Ruine & Decayes'. No vessels except fishing boats of 4 or 5 tons each manned by 6 or 7 fishermen (not mariners), used to catch herring after Michaelmas."}]

title: Anglesey
sources: [{"reference": "SP 12/39","date": "","folio": "76","notes": "No report for the west side of Anglesey, south of Holyhead and including Aberffraw and Malltraeth. BL Otho lists on this section of coast at an earlier period, '"The roode of St. Donwen is forland," and the three enterings there; the bay of Malltrayth, and the crick in the midst of the said bay; the crick of Aberfrowe; the crick of Crigille; the crick of Kemyran; the bay of Roscollyn, and the roode of the said forland of ...; St. Bride's bay'."}]

title: Denbighshire
sources: [{"reference": "SP 12/39","date": "8 Feb 1566","folio": "99","notes": "Included in Flintshire (Vorryd = Foryd at Rhuddlan)"}]

title: Pembrokeshire
sources: [{"reference": "SP 12/39","date": "8 Jan 1566","folio": "13-17v","notes": "Includes (f.17) a report of a 60-ton pirate ship in the haven of Milford."}]

title: Cumberland
sources: [{"reference": "SP 15/13","date": "20 Apr 1566","folio": "19r-20r","notes": "Fishermen living distant from the coast own boats of 1 ton, occupied by 4-6 men, catching herring & killinges. They do not use the creeks but land at their liberty elsewhere. At fishing time some vessels come from Chester, Liverpool and elsewhere bringing salt, iron, 'refuse wynes', and sometimes wines from Scotland for the provision of the honourable and worshipful houses of the county."}]

title: Sussex
